




TY  - JOUR
T1  - Adverse Selection, Commitment, and Renegotiation: Extension to and Evidence from Insurance Markets
AU  - Dionne, Georges
AU  - Doherty, Neil A.
Y1  - 1994/04/01
PY  - 1994
DA  - 1994/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261929
DO  - 10.1086/261929
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 209
EP  - 235
VL  - 102
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - With asymmetric information, full commitment to long-term contracts may permit markets to approach first-best allocations. However, commitment can be undermined by opportunistic behavior, notably renegotiation. We reexamine commitment in insurance markets. We present an alternative model (which extends Laffont and Tirole's procurement model to address uncertainty and competition), which involves semipooling in the first period followed by separation. This and competing models (e.g., single-period models and no-commitment models) have different predictions concerning temporal patterns of insurer profitability. A test using California data suggests that some automobile insurers use commitment to attract selective portfolios comprising disproportionate numbers of low risks.
AB  - With asymmetric information, full commitment to long-term contracts may permit markets to approach first-best allocations. However, commitment can be undermined by opportunistic behavior, notably renegotiation. We reexamine commitment in insurance markets. We present an alternative model (which extends Laffont and Tirole's procurement model to address uncertainty and competition), which involves semipooling in the first period followed by separation. This and competing models (e.g., single-period models and no-commitment models) have different predictions concerning temporal patterns of insurer profitability. A test using California data suggests that some automobile insurers use commitment to attract selective portfolios comprising disproportionate numbers of low risks.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261929
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261929
Y2  - 2024/03/23
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Evidence on Adverse Selection: Equilibrium Signaling and Cross-Subsidization in the Insurance Market
AU  - Puelz, Robert
AU  - Snow, Arthur
Y1  - 1994/04/01
PY  - 1994
DA  - 1994/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261930
DO  - 10.1086/261930
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 236
EP  - 257
VL  - 102
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - The configuration of equilibrium in the market for automobile collision insurance is examined empirically by representing the premium-deductible menu and the demand function as a standard hedonic system. Using contractual data from a representative insurer, we estimate a reduced-form hedonic premium equation and the inverse of the marginal bid equation for insurance coverage. The data reveal an equilibrium with adverse selection and market signaling but lead us to reject the hypothesis that high risks receive contracts subsidized by low risks.
AB  - The configuration of equilibrium in the market for automobile collision insurance is examined empirically by representing the premium-deductible menu and the demand function as a standard hedonic system. Using contractual data from a representative insurer, we estimate a reduced-form hedonic premium equation and the inverse of the marginal bid equation for insurance coverage. The data reveal an equilibrium with adverse selection and market signaling but lead us to reject the hypothesis that high risks receive contracts subsidized by low risks.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261930
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261930
Y2  - 2024/03/23
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Risk Aversion, Performance Pay, and the Principal-Agent Problem
AU  - Haubrich, Joseph G.
Y1  - 1994/04/01
PY  - 1994
DA  - 1994/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261931
DO  - 10.1086/261931
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 258
EP  - 276
VL  - 102
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper calculates numerical solutions to the principal-agent problem and compares the results to the stylized facts of CEO compensation. The numerical predictions come from parameterizing the models of Grossman and Hart and of Holmstrom and Milgrom. While the correct incentives for a CEO can greatly enhance a firm's performance, providing such incentives need not be expensive. For many parameter values, CEO compensation need increase only by about $10 for every $1,000 of additional shareholder value; for some values, the amount is 0.003 cents.
AB  - This paper calculates numerical solutions to the principal-agent problem and compares the results to the stylized facts of CEO compensation. The numerical predictions come from parameterizing the models of Grossman and Hart and of Holmstrom and Milgrom. While the correct incentives for a CEO can greatly enhance a firm's performance, providing such incentives need not be expensive. For many parameter values, CEO compensation need increase only by about $10 for every $1,000 of additional shareholder value; for some values, the amount is 0.003 cents.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261931
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261931
Y2  - 2024/03/23
